# 66_anim_handle_pump — OPENS the welcome-demo animation arc (s288 m1).
#
# The welcome demo banked in HANDOFF.md s287→s288 ("Banked for end-of-
# Curvz") needs a load-bearing primitive: a timed-motion pump that
# drives a real model value toward a target over a duration, with the
# canvas redrawing each frame. Every visible beat of the eventual
# demo — anchor placement, handle extension, segment growth, opacity
# crossfade, fade-delete — composes the same pump with a different
# per-tick callback.
#
# m1 ships the primitive and proves it works on one handle of one
# anchor. If the pump's timeout→mutate→redraw loop is smooth on this
# minimal case, every subsequent welcome-demo milestone is structural
# copies of the same pattern. If it isn't smooth — if there's a
# redraw barrier, a signal-loop fight, a Canvas-update timing issue —
# we find out on ~30 lines of script instead of after building 800
# lines of orchestrator.
#
# ── Shape ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# The script:
#   1. Switches to the Node tool (so handles are visibly rendered).
#   2. Mints a test layer, activates it.
#   3. Mints a Path object.
#   4. Sets its path data to a single anchor at the page centre, with
#      both handles initially collapsed at the anchor.
#   5. Calls `animate_handle 0 "out" 200 200 2000` — drive the out-
#      handle from (150, 150) to (200, 200) in user-space, over 2
#      seconds.
#   6. Script ends.
#
# After the script returns, the animation continues to run on the GTK
# main loop via Glib::Timeout. Scott sees the out-handle slide
# diagonally outward from the anchor over two seconds.
#
# ── No teardown ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Unlike most owns-its-conditions smokes, this one does NOT tear down
# the layer / path / anchor at the end. The animation lives PAST the
# script's natural end — the pump self-holds via shared_ptr into the
# timeout closure, and tearing down the path mid-animation would
# remove the model state the pump is writing into. (Per the verb's
# defensive shape, this is safe — the pump's tick re-resolves by iid
# and no-ops if the node is gone — but the visual result would be the
# handle disappearing mid-slide, which masks whether the primitive
# is working.)
#
# Scott manually closes the test layer (or just closes the doc) after
# watching the animation complete. The smoke's purpose is the visual
# channel — a convergent-evidence acceptance, not an asserts-pass
# headcount.
#
# ── Three-channel acceptance ─────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Trace channel: the script runs to completion without errors. All
#   `objects new`, `set_path_data`, `animate_handle` dispatches show
#   `ok`. No `error` lines.
#
# Visual channel (THE load-bearing channel for m1): Scott runs the
#   script with the Scripter window's "Step" mode off (timed mode at
#   default 50ms delay) so the script completes quickly. Then watches
#   the canvas for ~2 seconds. The out-handle of the lone anchor
#   slides diagonally from on-top-of-the-anchor (collapsed) to a
#   visible up-and-to-the-right position. Motion is smooth, not
#   stuttery. No flicker, no tearing, no visible model corruption.
#
# Build channel: Scott's compile.
#
# ── Why one anchor ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# A path with a single BezierNode is a degenerate case (no segments,
# nothing to fill or stroke), but the Node tool's overlay renders the
# anchor and its handles regardless. That's exactly what we need: the
# visible artifact is the anchor + handle, not any geometry between
# anchors. A two-anchor path would work too but introduces a second
# variable (the segment growing as the handles change shape it).
# Keep m1's variable count to one.
#
# ── Page-relative coords ─────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# The smoke assumes the default new-document page size; the anchor at
# (150, 150) lands roughly mid-page on most defaults. If the user
# happens to have a smaller doc loaded, the anchor still places
# correctly; only the visual centring is affected. The animation
# from (150, 150) → (200, 200) is a 50-unit offset on each axis,
# legible at any reasonable zoom.
#
# ── No sleep at end ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Tempting to add `sleep 2500` at the end so the animation completes
# before the script's done-marker fires. But the existing `sleep`
# uses g_usleep, which BLOCKS the main loop — exactly what would
# PREVENT the Glib::Timeout-driven animation from firing during the
# sleep. A non-blocking `wait` verb is backlog (logged on s288 m1
# close); m1 lets the animation run past script-end.
#
# ── Verbs exercised ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# `tb_nod click`              — toolbar tool selection (substrate)
# `layers new` + `activate`   — layer mint (s225 et al.)
# `objects new "path"`        — Path mint (s231 m2)
# `objects.<iid> set_path_data` — geometry seed (s236 m1)
# `objects.<iid> animate_handle` — THE NEW VERB (s288 m1)

#[sub] === Phase 1: Switch to Node tool ===
#[sub] Make handles visible by selecting the Node tool. Without this,
#[sub] the canvas renders only the path's stroke/fill (here: nothing,
#[sub] since the path has no segments), and the handle's motion would
#[sub] be invisible.

tb_nod click
assert tb_nod active == true

#[sub] === Phase 2: BUILD UP — mint test layer ===

layers new
set test_layer to result
layers.test_layer rename "anim_handle_pump_smoke_s288_m1"
layers.test_layer activate

#[sub] === Phase 3: BUILD UP — mint Path with one anchor ===
#[sub] Single BezierNode at user-space (500, 500) — centre of a
#[sub] 1000×1000 page. The d-string "M 500 500" parses to one
#[sub] anchor with both handles collapsed at the anchor
#[sub] (cx1=cy1=cx2=cy2=anchor.x/anchor.y). After s237 m1, user-
#[sub] space coords land Y-flipped in doc-space.

objects new "path"
set p to result
objects.p set_path_data "M 500 500"

assert objects.p type == "path"
assert objects.p node_count == 1

#[sub] === Phase 4a: SEED — snap the out-handle to a visible start ===
#[sub] A handle collapsed at its anchor (cx2 == anchor.x,
#[sub] cy2 == anchor.y) draws nothing — the renderer sees "handle is
#[sub] zero units from anchor" and the handle-dot overdraws the
#[sub] anchor-dot with no line between them. To make the animation
#[sub] visible from frame one, snap-seed the out-handle to (600, 600)
#[sub] first — that's 100 user-units up-right of the anchor, so the
#[sub] Node-tool overlay draws a visible handle line from (500, 500)
#[sub] to (600, 600).
#[sub]
#[sub] Same animate_handle verb, with duration=0. MotionPump's
#[sub] degenerate-duration branch fires one immediate tick at t=1.0
#[sub] and returns — equivalent to a snap-set. No timeout installed,
#[sub] no self-hold. The shape of the orchestration matches Phase 4b
#[sub] below; only the duration differs.

objects.p animate_handle 0 "out" 600 600 0

#[sub] === Phase 4b: ANIMATE — slide the out-handle to a new target ===
#[sub] Drive the out-handle from (600, 600) — its current position
#[sub] after Phase 4a — to (800, 300) over 2000 ms. That's a 200-unit
#[sub] X swing and a 300-unit Y swing, both unambiguous. The handle
#[sub] line visibly rotates and lengthens as the tip moves.
#[sub]
#[sub] Visual expectation: at the moment Phase 4a runs, a handle line
#[sub] appears from (500, 500) anchor to (600, 600) tip — pointing
#[sub] up-right. Then over 2 seconds, the tip slides smoothly from
#[sub] (600, 600) to (800, 300) — moving right AND down. The handle
#[sub] line stays connected to the anchor at its base and rotates
#[sub] downward as the tip moves.

objects.p animate_handle 0 "out" 800 300 2000

#[sub] === Script-end ===
#[sub] Script returns here. Animation continues on the main loop.
#[sub] Scott watches the handle slide for ~2 seconds, then has a
#[sub] static anchor + extended out-handle in the test layer. No
#[sub] teardown — closing the test layer or doc cleans up.
